          "body": "The oracle's final accusation is the most theologically escalating. Edom said of Israel's mountains: 'They are laid desolate; they are given to us for food' (35:12). This is not merely political commentary — it is contemptuous speech about the territory God had promised to His people. Ezekiel's devastating move in verse 13 is to equate the two: 'you have spoken arrogantly against Me and have multiplied your words against Me.' What Edom said about the mountains, it said about the mountains' Owner. This equation — contempt for God's land = contempt for God — is the climax of the indictment. It parallels what Jesus will articulate about His people in Matthew 25:45: 'Truly I say to you, to the extent that you did not do it to one of the least of these, you did not do it to Me.' God identifies with His covenant inheritance. The closing verdict (35:14-15) mirrors Edom's joy with precision: 'as you rejoiced over the inheritance of the house of Israel because it was desolate, so I will do to you.' The instrument of measurement is Edom's own emotion — the intensity of its Schadenfreude determines the depth of its judgment."
