        "title": "Words against the mountains, words against the LORD — and the lex talionis of joy",
        "range": "35:12-15",
        "excerpt": "You have spoken arrogantly against Me and have multiplied your words against Me; I have heard it. As you rejoiced over the inheritance of the house of Israel because it was desolate, so I will do to you.",
        "body": "The oracle's climax is a theological identification that escalates the entire indictment. Edom's words against the mountains of Israel — 'They are laid desolate; they are given to us for food' (35:12) — are reclassified in verse 13 as words against God Himself: 'you have spoken arrogantly against Me.' The equation is precise: the mountains of Israel are not merely a piece of territory but the inheritance of the covenant people, inseparable from the identity of the covenant God. To mock the desolation of the land is to mock the LORD who gave it. The same identification runs through the Psalms (79:1-4; 137:1-7) and the prophets (Isaiah 49:14-16, where Zion's abandonment is answered by God saying 'I have inscribed you on the palms of My hands').\n\nThe closing verses (35:14-15) deploy the oracle's most powerful rhetorical move: the as-so lex talionis applied to emotion rather than action. 'As all the earth rejoices, I will make you a desolation. As you rejoiced over the inheritance of the house of Israel because it was desolate, so I will do to you.' The word for rejoiced — simchah in verse 15 — is the noun form of the joy-vocabulary, the gladness at another's calamity that the book of Proverbs warns against (Proverbs 17:5; 24:17-18). In Ezekiel's oracle, that gladness becomes the precise measuring instrument for the judgment: Edom's desolation will be as complete as its joy was malicious.\n\nThe recognition formula closes the entire oracle: 'Then they will know that I am the LORD' (35:15). Note the shift: earlier units said 'you will know' (Edom); the final line says 'they will know' — the audience widens. The nations, Israel, all of history will come to knowledge through what happens to Edom. Tim Keller's observation about Ezekiel's oracles-against-the-nations applies precisely here: God's judgments are not local transactions but universal disclosures. Every verdict against injustice, exploitation, and arrogance is simultaneously an announcement about who God is. The desolation of Mount Seir is the back-side of the restoration of Israel's mountains — the two chapters are one theological event seen from two sides.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Gadal* (you boasted, v.13) — literally 'made large your mouth.' *Simchah* (joy, rejoicing, v.15) — the noun form of samach (v.14); both words in close proximity emphasize the emotional core of the final accusation. *Laken* (therefore) and *ken* (so) bracket the lex talionis conclusion — as you did, so it will be done to you."
